  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "The Possessive Construction (Idafa)",
      "titleArabic": "الإِضَافَة",
      "content": [
        "Arabic expresses possession by placing two nouns together. The first noun (mudāf) is the thing possessed, and the second (mudāf ilayhi) is the possessor.",
        "In an idafa construction, the first noun loses its tanwīn and takes a simple damma, while the second noun takes kasra (genitive case). The first noun is made definite by its relationship to the second."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "The possessor comes after the possessed: بَيْتُ الرَّجُلِ (the man's house)",
        "The first noun (mudāf) never takes ال or tanwīn",
        "The second noun (mudāf ilayhi) is in the genitive case (-i ending)",
        "The entire phrase is definite if the second noun is definite"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "بَيْتُ الرَّجُلِ", "english": "the man's house" },
        { "arabic": "كِتَابُ الْمُدَرِّسِ", "english": "the teacher's book" },
        { "arabic": "بَابُ الْمَسْجِدِ", "english": "the door of the mosque" },
        { "arabic": "مِفْتَاحُ السَّيَّارَةِ", "english": "the car's key" }
      ]
    }
  ],
